03914nam a22004815i 9780804764322DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047643227 a10.1515/97808047643222doi  a(DE-B1597)581886  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN68.M55 2001eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a801/.95/09041 aMiller, J. Hillis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpeech Acts in Literature /cJ. Hillis Miller. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMeridian: Crossing Aesthetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tI.J. L. Austin -- t2. Jacques Derrida -- t3. Paul de Man -- t4. Passion Performative -- t5. Marcel Proust -- tCoda: Allegory as Speech Act -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tCrossing Aesthetics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book demonstrates the presence of literature within speech act theory and the utility of speech act theory in reading literary works. Though the founding text of speech act theory, J. L. Austin's How to Do Things with Words, repeatedly expels literature from the domain of felicitous speech acts, literature is an indispensable presence within Austin's book. It contains many literary references but also uses as essential tools literary devices of its own: imaginary stories that serve as examples and imaginary dialogues that forestall potential objections. How to Do Things with Words is not the triumphant establishment of a fully elaborated theory of speech acts, but the story of a failure to do that, the story of what Austin calls a "bogging down." After an introductory chapter that explores Austin's book in detail, the two following chapters show how Jacques Derrida and Paul de Man in different ways challenge Austin's speech act theory generally and his expulsion of literature specifically. Derrida shows that literature cannot be expelled from speech acts—rather that what he calls "iterability" means that any speech act may be literature. De Man asserts that speech act theory involves a radical dissociation between the cognitive and positing dimensions of language, what Austin calls language's "constative" and "performative" aspects. Both Derrida and de Man elaborate new speech act theories that form the basis of new notions of responsible and effective politico-ethical decision and action. The fourth chapter explores the role of strong emotion in effective speech acts through a discussion of passages in Derrida, Wittgenstein, and Austin. The final chapter demonstrates, through close readings of three passages in Proust, the way speech act theory can be employed in an illuminating way in the accurate reading of literary works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLiterary Studies -- General Criticism and Theory. 4aPhilosophy -- Poststructuralism and Phenomenology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476432240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764322/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles